===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|emeraude|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|esmeraude|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|VL.|en}} {{term/t|la|*esmaralda}}, {{term/t|la|*esmaraldus}}, variant of {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|smaragdus|lang=la}}, from {{etyl|grc|en}} {{term|σμάραγδος|lang=grc}}, {{term|μάραγδος|lang=grc|tr=maragdos}}, from Semitic root ''b-r-q'' “to shoot lightning, to flash in darkness”, compare {{etyl|he|-}} {{term|בָּרֶקֶת|tr=bareket|lang=he}} “emerald, flashing gem”, Akkadian {{term|tr=barruktu|lang=akk}}, Arabic ''buraq'' “lightning”. {{rfscript|und|sc=Arab}} {{etyl|sa|-}} {{term|मरकत|tr=marakata|lang=sa}} from a Semitic language. Persian {{term|زمرد|lang=fa|tr=zomorrod}} (whence Turkish {{term|zümrüt|lang=tr}}, whence Russian {{term|изумруд|lang=ru|tr=izumrud}} from Ancient Greek {{term|σμάραγδος|lang=grc|tr=smaragdos}}.

